        &nbsp;<a href="post.asp?method=ReplyQuote&REPLY_ID=69016&TOPIC_ID=8545&FORUM_ID=1&CAT_ID=1&Forum_Title=General+Discussions&Topic_Title=Warning+to+Win98+Users&M="><img src="icon_reply_topic.gif" height=15 width=15 alt="Reply with Quote" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>


        <hr noshade size="1">
        
        <font color="white" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size="2">Here's the fix.</P><P>Find out how much system RAM you have. Multiply this by 1.5. Right this number down.</P><P>For win 98 users Right Click on My Computer<BR>Select Properties<BR>Select Performance<BR>Select Virtual Memory<BR>Select Let me Specify My own Setting<BR>Select Disable Virtual Memory<BR>Now click yes to the boxes that pop up. This will reboot your CPU.<BR>When it comes back up. Do this<BR>Click start.<BR>Select Run<BR>Type Defrag<BR>Now sit back and let this defragment your Hard Drive.<BR>Once this is done, follow the first steps until you get to the part after selecting Virtual Memory.<BR>Now instead of disabling Virtual Memory, you want to make both the Lower and Upper limits that number that you wrote down. This will create a unfragmented non sizeable Swap File of the optimum proportion to your available RAM.</P><P>Reboot and then do this.</P><P>Click Start:<BR>Select RUN<BR>Type sysedit<BR>This will bring up a box with several windows in it.<BR>Select the window that says c:\windows\system.ini<BR>scroll down in that window until you see a line that looks like this<BR>[386Enh]</P><P>Now under that type this<BR>ConservativeSwapfileUsage=1</P><P>Save this and reboot.</P><P>You should see a significant increase in performance.</P><P>54 Heretic GuildMaster of the Dark Legion(Povar)<a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height=15 width=15 border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
